# This is a TEMPLATE — variable names with empty values, no real secrets.
# Copy to deploy/.env and fill in. deploy/.env is gitignored (never committed) AND
# excluded from the Docker build context (never baked into the image); compose's
# env_file injects it into the running container at RUNTIME.
#
# The framework reads ${env:VAR} from the environment; .env is just one source.
# To see the EXACT env vars a manifest needs, run:
#   docker compose -f deploy/docker-compose.yml run --rm collector paramify describe <fetcher>
#   docker compose -f deploy/docker-compose.yml run --rm collector paramify run examples/minimal_run.yaml
# (the runner reports which secrets/config are still missing).

# ---- Option A: pull everything from AWS Secrets Manager (recommended) --------
# Instead of listing secrets below, point at an SM secret (or comma-separated
# list) holding a JSON object of VAR->value. The entrypoint hydrates them at
# startup using the container's AWS role (IRSA / task role / instance role).
# PARAMIFY_SECRETS_ID=paramify/fetchers/beta
# AWS_REGION=us-east-1

# ---- Option B: provide values directly (below) -------------------------------
# ---- Upload to Paramify (required for the upload step) -----------------------
PARAMIFY_UPLOAD_API_TOKEN=
# Optional; defaults to stage (https required, except localhost):
# PARAMIFY_API_BASE_URL=https://stage.paramify.com/api/v0

# ---- Per-platform credentials (uncomment what your manifests actually use) ---
# Names below are illustrative — confirm each with `paramify describe <fetcher>`.
# Okta
# OKTA_ORG_URL=
# OKTA_API_TOKEN=
# KnowBe4
# KNOWBE4_API_KEY=
# KNOWBE4_REGION=us
# GitLab
# GITLAB_TOKEN_1=
# AWS — prefer an instance role / IRSA over static keys; passthrough is wired in
# fetchers/_categories/aws.yaml. If you must use static keys:
# AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1
